<p><b>Scoliosis</b> (from <a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a>: <i><a href="/wiki/Romanization_of_Greek" title="Romanization of Greek">skolíōsis</a></i> meaning "crooked")<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> is a medical condition in which a person's <a href="/wiki/Vertebral_column" title="Vertebral column">spine</a> is curved from side to side, shaped like a "s", and may also be rotated. To adults it can be very painful. It is an abnormal lateral curvature of the spine. On an x-ray, the spine of an individual with a typical scoliosis may look more like an "S" or a "C" than a straight line. It is typically classified as <a href="/wiki/Congenital" title="Congenital" class="mw-redirect">congenital</a> (caused by vertebral anomalies present at birth), <a href="/wiki/Idiopathic" title="Idiopathic">idiopathic</a> (sub-classified as infantile, juvenile, adolescent, or adult according to when onset occurred) or as having developed as a secondary symptom of another condition, such as <a href="/wiki/Cerebral_palsy" title="Cerebral palsy">cerebral palsy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Spinal_muscular_atrophy" title="Spinal muscular atrophy">spinal muscular atrophy</a> or due to <a href="/wiki/Physical_trauma" title="Physical trauma">physical trauma</a>.</p>
